    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1965-01-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1965-01-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="21"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d21">
                <head>21. Memorandum From Terrence Scanlon of <persName corresp="#p_MJW2"
                        type="from">John W. Macy Jr.</persName>’s Staff to <persName type="to">John
                        B. Clinton</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d21fn1">Source: Johnson Library, Office Files
                        of <persName corresp="#p_MJW2">John Macy</persName>, Box 693, State
                        Dept-General-1965. No classification marking. Along with his duties as
                        Chairman of the Civil Service Commission, <persName corresp="#p_MJW2"
                            >Macy</persName> served as President <persName corresp="#p_JLB1"
                            >Johnson</persName>’s chief talent scout for Presidential appointments.
                        Scanlon and Clinton were members of the staff that assisted him in that
                        responsibility, the latter serving as <persName corresp="#p_MJW2"
                            >Macy</persName>’s Executive Assistant. The personnel files created in
                        discharging that responsibility are at the Johnson Library.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1965-01-26">January 26, 1965</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>This is the reply to Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MJW2">Macy</persName>’s request
                    that we verify Congressman Adam Clayton Powell’s statistics (attached letter of
                    December 18 addressed to the President)<note n="2" xml:id="d21fn2">Not
                        found.</note> pertaining to the number of Negro executives in his selected
                    departments and agencies. I have contacted HEW, HHFA, the Peace Corps and the
                    State Department.</p>
                <table cols="2" rows="2">
                    <row>
                        <cell>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mr. Powell’s Figures Department of State:</hi>
                        </cell>
                        <cell>
                            <hi rend="italic">Agency Reply</hi>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>The United States is currently represented in its diplomatic relations
                            and international activities by 110 ambassadors, 2 ministers and 5
                            ambassadors to special missions. Of that total of 117, there are only
                            two Negroes. They are Mercer Cook, Ambassador to Senegal and Clinton
                            Knox, Ambassador to Dahomey. This represents a loss of one from the
                            number of Negro ambassadors in the <persName corresp="#p_KJF2"
                                >Kennedy</persName> Administration which not only achieved the
                            highest number for the first time, but had assigned Negroes to important
                            ambassadorial posts, Finland (<persName corresp="#p_RCT1">Carl L.
                                Rowan</persName>) and Norway (Clifton Wharton, Sr.). The third Negro
                            ambassador then was Mercer Cook.</cell>
                        <cell>Congressman Powell’s criteria of “117” excludes Franklin Williams who
                            is the United States Representative to the Economic and Social Council,
                            United Nations who holds a personnel rank as ambassador ($27,000). There
                            are also two Negro Deputy Assistant Secretaries in the Department of
                            State: Samuel Westerfield, Deputy Assistant Secretary for African
                            Affairs and Charlotte Hubbard, Deputy Assistant for Public Affairs.
                            Chester Carter, who served as Deputy Assistant Secretary for
                            Congressional Relations, was promoted in May in 1964 as Deputy Chief of
                            Protocol. There are currently 9 Negroes holding positions of <gloss
                                target="#t_GS1">GS</gloss>–16 level and above in the Department of
                            State.</cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <pb facs="0082" n="48" xml:id="pg_48"/>
                <p>[Omitted here are similar discussions of African-Americans in the Peace Corps,
                    the Housing and Home Finance Agency, and the Department of Health, Education and
                    Welfare.]</p>
            </div>
